<Time>1486327600463</Time>< Text>
Kings as in "The L.A." two-time NFL champs.

The is a gem of a find right in the shadow of Warner Bros just off W. Olive on Pass Avenue and less than a block from the trendy (and pricey) Riverside Drive joints .  They mean "deli," too!  The sandwiches are thick, meaty, and creative; the lattes lovingly prepared (best ever!); and, the proprietors some of the friendliest and chattiest anywhere.  PLUS, discounts for union members and New York Film Academy students.<//Text>

< text>
The place has been around for 4 decades and just recently, they move to the downtown Santa Cruz location.

Just the first second I walked into the place, I already noticed it‚Äôs elegantly decorated and inviting.

I found their cupcakes are quite moist which I like! Though, a little bit too intensive on the sweetness for me. That‚Äôs why the most favorite out of the three of them I had is the Hibiscus flower. The deep red color of hibiscus frosting actually has that little sourness which helps with the too-sweet taste.

The Carrot Ginger was lovely too. The vegans would die for this. A vegan sweet treat that‚Äôs actually very delicious!

WAY BEYOND PAD THAI< /text>

If you are planning a wedding in the bay/coastal area, I HIGHLY recommend having Buttercup Cakes provide your wedding cake and/or desserts! <name>Max Pedroza<//name>< text>
Come here every now and then since it‚Äôs close to the house.

Today I ordered the regular bowl with tuna, salmon, and albacore. Also added edamame, cilantro, wasabi, and spicy Mayo.

The meal was tasty and the fish tasted fresh. The portion seemed small for the amount of money, especially compared to other poke locations nearby.

I recommend this place if you are in the area, but there are tastier places a bit further away in Westminster.< /text>

<review>I just went here for the first time after reading the positive reviews on here and I have to say...not impressed...if you know what quality sashimi/sushi taste like, save yourself from becoming repulsed by the quality of their fish here. The slimy texture and chewyness of the fish was repulsive. Not to mention, they charge almost $2 for literally a table spoon of avocado. I also was a little skeptical by how the place functions and serves the fish..it is a "subway style" system and for raw fish...I find that very unfresh, unappetizing and a little sketchy that the raw fish is just sitting out there. This is the very first review I have ever written in my life..and I am writing this not to bash the place but just to make others aware because by reading the rest of the reviews on here and then  discovering how terrible the quality of the fish was myself, I definitely feel that this place is slightly over rated when it comes to the reviews.<//review></record></dataset><record>

<review>If I could, I would have given it 3.5 stars just because it is a beautiful restaurant inside an even more beautiful hotel.  Gorgeous harbor view and the decore is nice, but very conservative (this is your grandparents restaurant).

Service was the best part of the night.  They were impeccable in their care, courteous, and very professional. Reminded me of Michelin starred French restaurants.

Unfortunately, food was very disappointing.  Dinner rolls looked grocery bought and cold (below room temperature).  Menu tries to be trendy, but it's about 5 years behind the times.  $35 to $60 for main course, but not very well prepared.  My white bass was thoughtlessly prepared without any flavor and my father's scallops were also very uninspired.  I wouldn't mind coming back to stay at the hotel, but I wouldn't come back here again.</review><Pics>None<//Pics>< resp>

Recently bought a new 16ft enclosed trailer for towing our Razor. While hooking it up for our 3rd trip to Nevada  I notice one tire had worn excessively on the inside. When I called to explained the situation they had me come down immediately to check it out. Unfortunately their mechanic was off that day so they installed a new tire and made sure I had a spare just in case. Long story short, they contacted the manufacturer and had me come back while they took detailed measurements provided by the manufacturer. They did this while I waited, not drop it off and leave it for days or weeks. They had a crew working on it and made sure it was all correct. End result was a defective tire. So Instead of replacing the one, which was acceptable to me, they replaced all 4 so I would have even wear  tires. They went above and beyond to make sure I was taken care of. I‚Äôm very impressed with the sales staff and mechanics and would highly recommend them for all your trailer needs. I believe they are affiliated with Ultra Truckworks across the street so no doubt you‚Äôd receive the same customer service shopping there as well.

<user_id>113242982329861461116< /user_id>< Text>
GREAT Sales Experience!

I don't often write reviews, but every now and then there's an experience that needs to be acknowledged. My brother and I's first trailer purchase at Sac-Valley Trailer with Bernie was one.

We had done a lot of research on dump trailers and thought Load-Trail was going to be the best option. My brother visited Bernie and got a good explanation and very fair price quote. We both went back on Friday to make the deal. Don't worry if it's raining...Bernie and his team will be there ready to help and make a deal! We had several questions and Bernie was awesome at sharing his opinion and thoughts on what was really needed and what wasn't. Not pushing a brand, but Bernie said this was a great trailer with a 2 year warranty and they were always available to help if anything went wrong.

Awesome experience and felt like it was a WIN-WIN for all parties. Thanks Bernie!<//Text>

<userid>107108240128732780454<//userid><review>Wife and I stopped here at 11 am on Sunday. Only ourselves and another couple were in the restaurant. Service was very slow but friendly. They seemed focused on filling orders for take out. Wife ordered cheese enchilada, taco and beans. I ordered a large menudo. It took an hour to bring our food. While we waited we were served mediocre chips and plain flavorless salsa. My menudo was a bit greasy but flavorful. Included in the menudo was hominy and a beef foot. Sides for the menudo included oregano, lemon, onion and parsley plus choice of corn or flour tortillas. Wife said her enchilada was ok but beans were very watery. Taco was generously filled with meat along with onion and cilantro. Total for two without drinks was $25.00. We stopped to try This place based on our daughter's recommendation but since competition is fierce in Oxnard. We will most likely return to our usual place which we prefer.<//review>< time>

<user_id>111695171342037958624<//user_id>< username>
Jake Nonnemaker<//username>
<Date>1579731831776<//Date>< Rate>
5</Rate>
< review>
I accidently stumbled upon Los Arcos when, after a day of sailing off the coast of Channel Islands harbor, I got a hankering for a burrito.  And what a wonderful surprise I discovered at Los Arcos!  The carne asada burrito was amazingly delicious, massive, and hit the spot; as a bonus, I got a Modelo to wash it down.

It was probably just a week later when I crafted some excuse to drive to Channel Islands harbor and visit Los Arcos again, but this time with my family.  On this trip I got a giant shrimp, octopus, and clam cocktail.  It was huge and delicious.  We also ordered al pastor, carnitas, and lengua tacos and an asada burrito.  Everyone was very satisfied with their food.

There many seafood dishes like shrimp in devil or garlic sauce, fish, and various seafood cocktails.  They offer a few different beers: 805, Bud or Coors Light, Corona, Modelo and Pacifico.  There are also aguas frescas: horchata, tamarindo and jamaica. And they make fresh orange and carrot juices.

Prices are right in line with good Mexican food.  Service is friendly and good and the food takes a few minutes to prepare but not long.  That‚Äôs why I get a bottle of beer and relax while I wait.

It appears that I‚Äôve created a new job for myself.  Whenever I‚Äôm in the Channel Islands harbor or Port Hueneme area, I‚Äôm now (happily) obligated to bring home Los Arcos for the family.</review>

<GmapID>0x80e84e6ceb0d8453:0x75e2bbc64b72ce2a< /GmapID><Time>1487290538178</Time><user_id>104674651574689638045<//user_id>< name>

<resp>None</resp>< Rating>
5< /Rating>
< text>
Sit down and serve type place or take out.
They have a happy hour, M-F 2-1 Coors light drafts and lower price on other. Good variety of Micheladas.
I really like the way they season their meat.
Salas a roja is fantastic.
They have a great salsa roja, fish/shrimp taco.they give U chips with sitting down.
I really dig their Asada fries (HUGE), and aren't on the menu!!!
YUMMMMMMMMM!!!!
New owners within a year or so.
Much improved! !!!
Yes, theirs lots of Mexican places in the Oxnard area.
This one, as far as the food is above the rest. Ambiance is average, they have 2 tv's.
For those who don't speak English,  not really any language barrier.</text>

<rate>5</rate>< Review>
It's been almost two years since we last traveled and to say I was nervous was an understatement. However,  SJC took a lot of safety precautions that helped alleviate my worries,  especially when traveling with my twin toddlers who are not currently vaccinated.  Mask are required and they ask that everyone maintains socially distant from one another.  In the security line,  they have plexiglass dividing security from travelers.  In the bathroom,  they've added dividers between each sink to ensure a more individualized space.  Chairs has sign to ensure that ppl are seated away from one another.  Security and employees at the airport were very friendly and helpful,  especially since we were traveling with a double stroller and toddlers who got confused with all that was happening around them.  We had a great experience at SJC, but then again,  we've airways had a positive experience here.  It's great to see the airport continue to expand and improve in the last two decade.<//Review>

<Review>Going through TSA Pre was a little different from before the pandemic. You have to wear a mask, show your ID, not your boarding pass, and when they have your information on screen, they ask that you pull down your mask so they can make sure it is you.

For Southwest, there is a watering station to fill up your bottle on the left. To the right is a Peets, Chick-fil-A, and further down, a Starbucks,  a Hudson News (where I got a turkey sandwich and some chips for our meal) and a sushi restaurant.  The Chick-fil-A was open by 7am and the line was long.

The lounge area was clean. And since the plane isn't full, it wasn't as crowded to line up for the plane.</Review><Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOyz-q7qceT5xF11J94G7s6J3glXdzEKSwCufh_=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipM0KVKCi8a2Tre9pTD5nevP1mWxQQ_fMs_sLAd_=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOvcoJyqtJfhh_Oe2q1I9OME7ZfKWk0sY8lOhDf=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</Pictures>< Resp>

This airport is easy to get to and very convenient.
It is a very friendly airport. You may ask anyone with questions or help.

Their Lost and Found office is amazing! I had left my laptop in a bin at TSA security check and they called me the next day that it was found and turned in.
I was instructed to fill out a from on the day I found out my laptop was missing. The form was online and was so easy to fill out and submit.

This airport is very organized especially for Uber.
I got picked by Uber easily and conveniently.

I recommend to everyone when you can to fly San Jose Airport.</text>

<response>None<//response><pics>None< /pics><rating>5</rating>< date>
1609173391117</date>
<Gmap_id>0x808fcbc3fab3c59b:0xbcfa443f6df67e3e< /Gmap_id></record></dataset><record>
<userid>108891609715473721271< /userid>< Review>
San Jose's airport is a great option if you're in the bay area. It's a little out of the way if you're heading to San Francisco or Oakland, but it is a lot less hectic and the terminal is in great shape.

I'm just traveling through, but I did have to get my bags from baggage claim and I will need to check them back in tomorrow morning (no connecting flight this evening.

Baggage claim consists of just two carousels so it's not too difficult to find which one is spewing forth luggage from your flight.

Check in is on the same level. Most of the food , drink, etc. vendors are in the terminal area that is past security, but there is a Starbucks and a little "marketplace" available by baggage claim if you need something when you're getting your bags.

Not sure about parking, but there appears to be a huge garage structure right across the street.

There is a sign for a USO, but all I could find was the Military Lounge, which is not a USO and is only for active duty military personnel. It's something the airport does for the military and is a nice thing.<//Review>
< time>
1571813952752<//time>

Greatest airport ever. A lot smaller and less busy than SFO. TSA lines are non-existent and the gates are right after security. It takes about 10 minutes to walk in, get through security including unpacking my bags and taking my clothes off, redressing and repacking carry-ons, and walking to the gate. This is the speed and efficiency I wish I always had at airports! I love flying in and out of SJC when I need to go to the bay area! Except on Sundays because Chick-fil-A is closed üòè<//Text>

<userid>116850517393216923352<//userid><username>Tim Riener</username><time>1604457899353< /time><Rating>4< /Rating>< Text>
Back in the day... That is before Corona virus took over... When I had to do a lot of day trip traveling down to southern California, this airport was ideal. I could park in a parking lot that was literally butted up against the terminal and I could go from my car to the TSA line in under 3 minutes. Getting in and out was a fair breeze. The interior of the terminal could use some work geometrically I mean. It's one long line of gates on one side and shops on the other. Which means you might have to walk 20 gates to get to your favorite Starbucks or restaurant. All in all though, pretty good airport.<//Text>

<Date>1607139728189<//Date>< Rate>
5< /Rate>
<Pics>None</Pics>< Text>
In our experience, this airport has been infinitely more pleasant than SFO. If there is any way that we can possibly travel via SJC instead of SFO, we do so. Overall, we find SJC cleaner, more convenient and friendlier.

Many of the negative reviews seem to concern the TSA personnel. I think it's important we understand that they are not well compensated and much is asked of them in return, with many passengers not paying them the courtesy they deserve. If we all make an effort to be courteous, we will receive more courtesy in return.

It also speaks well of SJC that negative reviews here are conscientiously responded to, typically with offers to contact appropriate parties, to follow up on issues that deserve attention.

TIP: We ourselves did experience some issues relating to our unfamiliarity with the layout and the parking system. I would highly encourage anyone using this airport for the first time to make an effort to check things out online before their trip -- and always arrive earlier, to allow for possible missteps.

As Roy Rogers used to sing, "Happy trails to you!"</Text>
< Name>
Daniel Berman</Name>

<rating>3</rating>< Text>
Cute little airport. If you're going to Silicon Valley (Palo Alto, Mountain View etc.) on a domestic flight, flights to this airport is usually slightly cheaper. There's a train going all the way to San Francisco, too. Despite so close to the center of tech, things move rather slowly here. They need people from the valley to bring some disruption to this airport.< /Text>

108074935470209044442<//user>
<user_name>Mahesh Paolini-Subramanya</user_name>< date>
1516375699386<//date>
<Rating>4<//Rating>< text>
It's all about the gates - and in this case, the gate structure is pretty good. Plenty of security lanes, efficient TSAPre, and the traffic through the gates tends to be low enough that you usually get through in 5.minutes or less (way less, with TSAPre).

Inside, there really isn't much in the way of amenities - just the usual assortments of Peets, Starbucks, chain restaurants, etc.

That's ok though - the key here is to come in hot (get here with just enough time to make it through the gates, and onto the plane üòÄ< /text>

<date>1581618684027< /date><Rating>4</Rating>< text>
There are many areas to talk about when it comes to an airport. From the design to the operations, and to the amenities within. So instead of bore you with the details, here are a few useful bullets.
- Small airport, but everything is reachable within a small distance.
- Connected terminals so accessing different amenities are possible.
- Fast Internet (most of the time).
- Very decent lounges if you have access. (occasional restrictions).
- Lower flight cadence when compared to bigger airports like SFO.
- Less airline options when compared to bigger airports like SFO.<//text>

< text>
As far as airports go, this was one of the best experiences I've ever had. I wish going through an airport was always this good.

Leave it up to Silicon Valley to have such a sleek, modern, and sexy  airport as this. It is not large, which makes drop off and finding your gate quite easy. There is not a frantic feel here. Laid out well, everything is easy to find, and it is spotless clean.

< user>
116787012649916667934<//user>
<name>noodlenoggin</name><Date>1595443438162</Date><rating>5<//rating>< Review>
I've had a couple of long-term projects in the Bay Area, and my airport of choice is SJC.  San Francisco may have better dining and shopping, but SJC is 100% better at being on-time with their core business of airplanes landing and taking off.  Served by the major airlines, and a huge Southwest hub, if you fly Southwest, there are nearly as many tickets to SJC as to the larger SFO.  Plus, the terminal is super-easy to navigate -- it's just one long concourse -- you can walk inside security from the end of Terminal A, all the way through Terminal B.  Plus, the rental car center is just across the road from Terminal B.  Consistently, I'm able to return my rental car, walk across the road, get through Terminal B security (Pre Check), and walk the length of the airport to my flight in Terminal A...all in far less than a half-hour.< /Review>

< review>
Good airport.
Little bit small but very convenient if you are flying from San Jose or nearby area.
All nearby people uses this for domestic travel.
Not much long haul flights, but you can get connecting international flights, which'll be ok if you are ok to add 1 more stop in your route.

My company is in San Jose and they routes international flights also via this airport as this is convenient for everyone.< /review>

<Time>1516375699386< /Time>< Pictures>
[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNEBt3HLlW5of7LTUWOYMdCu7GSouiELT0Om1_H=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPqHY8yjWlmt06CWCsU06gXmZ5JeWaF0wkfuk5V=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOsofE2wuYUjloC2QNOlqObjK3ygIzdrVCRoWBf=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPpP9aXLa15b5cnBT18JS-O5xZ_GzNJZ8uxPt_T=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /Pictures>
< review>
It's all about the gates - and in this case, the gate structure is pretty good. Plenty of security lanes, efficient TSAPre, and the traffic through the gates tends to be low enough that you usually get through in 5.minutes or less (way less, with TSAPre).

Inside, there really isn't much in the way of amenities - just the usual assortments of Peets, Starbucks, chain restaurants, etc.

That's ok though - the key here is to come in hot (get here with just enough time to make it through the gates, and onto the plane üòÄ<//review>

<user_name>Paulina Lei<//user_name><time>1497983686374< /time>< Rate>
4< /Rate>
< review>
San Jose airport is not bad. Overall, it is a well-organized airport. Check-ins are usually fast. During popular times of travel, it can be a little busy, but it's a lot better than other airports in terms of handling the large amount of traffic.

The structural design of the airport is a little flawed. If you have a gate that is a small number like 1-9, you have to walk the entire length of the airport to get to your gate. But, can't really complain about this since this is the design.

Most of the time, it is rather clean. However, I have been there a few times and looked under the seats and found some trash.

Restaurants there are quite nice, too. Of course, the airport prices aren't cheap.</review>
<pics>None< /pics>< Resp>
None< /Resp>
< gmap_id>
0x808fcbc3fab3c59b:0xbcfa443f6df67e3e<//gmap_id>
</record>
</dataset><record>
<user_id>106206511677592870990< /user_id>< Review>
I've only flown in and out of this airport once..and I am a fan..

The airport is big enough so there's plenty of room for numerous gates for enough flights in and out of San Jose.  However, it's not so big where gates are separated by buildings and you have to get there by a railed tram or long walks.  The tall glass ceilings allow light to naturally come in and make for an attractive airport.

There's pretty good dining options lined up at Mineta should you need to grab a bite.  The TSA Pre-check line is efficient and gets you through quickly.  They had two Pre-check stations operating when I went through at 7 PM.  There's a cool rotating airplane influenced art piece right outside the security check.  It's a social media moment for sure.

This is the best airport to rent a car from.  The rental car area is literally across the street.  After less than a 10 minute walk, you're in the rental car building lobby.  Fantastic.

Overall, Mineta San Jose Airport is a well designed medium sized airport.  I don't fly here often, but I would have no issues flying to Mineta when need be.  Safe Travels!< /Review>

< Rating>

<Review>This airport does its job and it does it well. It's much easier and less stressful to navigate than SFO. There are ample food options past security. From arriving at the airport to reaching the gate must have taken around 25-30 minutes max on a lazy Thursday morning.

The only somewhat annoying thing about SJC is that it's not particularly easy to get to from the rest of the Bay Area via public transit - you have to take the Caltrain to San Jose Diridon station and then either take a city bus or take the VTA light rail - not bad, but not great either. But if you are ok with either struggling through public transit or taking an Uber/taxi, then this may just be the best airport in the Bay area.<//Review><pics>None</pics><resp>None< /resp><gmapID>0x808fcbc3fab3c59b:0xbcfa443f6df67e3e<//gmapID></record></dataset><record>
<name>Jayson Jenson< /name><Pictures>None</Pictures>< user>
107094166762469904983< /user>
<Rating>4<//Rating>< resp>
None</resp>
<time>1575567069718</time>< Text>
Access to this airport is pretty simple from major freeways (101, 87, 17/880). Plenty of short/long term parking. While other airport options exist nearby (SF, Oakland, Monterey) I prefer SJC.
- I predominately travel using American Airlines who has an Admirals Club here and reasonable flight schedule options (although it was better years ago when  SJC was an American hub location). Inside the secured area (where the Gates are, thru TSA) there are plenty of small shops, places for food, both a Peets and $tarBucks coffee, book stores and restrooms.
- I've never had an issue where arriving at least 3 hours before your flight was required (although I did get burned once on a codeshare American flight serviced by Alaskan Airlines who refused me a boarding pass because their self-serve machines were down and waiting in line I got to their ticket counter only 40 minutes before flight time, so I had to schlep my bags back over to the Ametican terminal where they confirmed that if it had been at an American Gate that they would have issued me a boarding pass as long as the Jetbridge door for that flight was still open (and they apologized for their "partner's" overly aggressive rule). American then re-routed my itinerary for free putting me on different/alternate American flights (ones that would have been more expensive if I had booked them) that got me where I was going on-time and gave me upgraded preferred seats - again for free, AND they were done BEFORE my original flight departed (in other words in less than what was left of those 40 minutes even including the inter-terminal foot travel excursion).
- Bottomline is ANYtime there has been any unplanned travel complication (like, equipment/weather canceled flights) American has always taken care of me (arranging ground transportation to a nearby quality hotel, providing dinner vouchers, re-booking onto first thing next morning direct flight to my original location in upgraded seating - all at $0 to me). SJC continues to be my preferred home base.</Text>

< username>
Steve C</username>
<UserId.>115287976961006879144</UserId.><Time>1571790071663< /Time>< review>
The facilities are modern with bathrooms spaced evenly along the concourse. Good variety of restaurants. However, due to airport real estate, the terminal is very linear. That is, all the gates are spread out in a line. The parking, car rental, arrivals and departures for domestic flights are all located across from gate 26. If you land at gate 17 or lower number, you have to walk quite a distance to get to the exit.

There is only one security checkpoint in Terminal B.  Clear, TSA Pre check, and general have separate lines, but all are still funneled through the one area (maybe 5 x-ray lines total of all are open, one or two dedicated to Clear/TSA Pre). This wait can be long for security, depending on the day/time. Note: I have not been in Terminal A (international).< /review>

<user>115031961687750581059</user>< text>
I love flying in an out of SJC. There is rarely any lines at security to the point where it's faster to go in the regular line than the pre-check line. Because it's still relatively small geographically speaking, you can get from curbside to the gate in less than 20 minutes if you aren't checking a bag. The lines to check bags are also practically non-existent across multiple airlines (american, United, JetBlue, etc), so even if you have to go that route, it won't add too much time. There aren't many food options inside or outside of security so I'd recommend eating before you arrive. However they have a few decent bars so come thirsty.< /text>

< Review>
This airport is tucked away in San Jose and is pretty nice. Due to its location in Silicon Valley there are plenty of tech savey travellers and the bells and whistles to go with them. The loading and unloading zone is fairly busy and could use expansion but other than that everything feels easy going and smooth. The building Is modelled after an airplane hanger and is laid out as a long line with gates laid out along one side. This was wisely done so that travel between terminals is fast. If you have this airport as a choice I would recommend it over many others.< /Review>

< rating>

<UserId.>103070753730493610964</UserId.><name>Arnold Flores<//name>< Text>
I love the silicon valley airport. Easy in and out.

Parking is abundant.  Lot 1 is closed due to renovations. However, the long term lots near Southwest airline is open and price dropped to $18 per day.

Lot's of restaurants, cocktail, beer and coffee options available in the terminals.

Wait times in lines going through security are very fast, with wait times less than 10 minutes.

A layover of 3+ hours allows me to travel down the street (10 minutes) to grab a bite. I may also travel 15 minutes into downtown to walk or grab a quick bite.

Longer layovers can travel to the Westfield Valley Fair shopping center and to the famous Santana Row - (5 miles) 10 minutes drive or by Uber/Lyft.  Great place to shop, eat and walk for an hour.

Great airport.< /Text>
</record></dataset><record>

This is partially because most of the time you can get through this airport fairly quickly compared to other airports. The city not investing in a people mover (or two) is utterly ridiculous and does a disservice to the city, Silicon Valley, and everyone who utilizes this supposedly high tech airport. So be prepared (possibly) for long terminal walks (exercise). Food and shopping selections are not great. I agree that the roadways/signage are ridiculous and poorly designed. < text>
A nice regional airport. Much more relaxed and less hustle bustle than SFO up the bay. It's a fairly long walk typically from the far ends of the terminal to the luggage reclaim. There's a decent amount of shops, security is very fast (early morning in particular / of course) and there's fun little things like the perpetual engine science machine in the lounge to distract from the wait.
Flew with Delta back to Dublin and had no issues. Also good to see water bottle refill points, so no messing with fountains and fighting to angle it juuusst right.
Decent medium sized airport for connecting from International flights.<//text>

<review>What's not love? Beautiful architecture, comfortable seating, friendly-knowledgeable staff and for an international airport, small. Even the long lines at TSA are short. This is the center of the digital world.  (Google, Apple and just about every other digital company is nearby.)  Almost every oversized chair is equipped with a power station. Check-out their well designed, easy to use website. Excellent selection of food services. (Many healthy choices, including vegan and gluten-free.) Of course, everything is wheelchair accessible. Lots of easy, expensive parking. Rates range from $18.00 to $30.00 USD daily. Coupons are available on the internet to cut the price in half.  Free, off-site, cell phone parking lot is offered.  Gender-neutral and single-gender bathrooms throughout the facility.  Uber, Lyft and many choices of ground transportation are available. Auto rentals can be slow.</review></record></dataset><record>

<rating>3< /rating>< Text>
Airport is dated, and not high tech. Had higher expectations for my first visit to Silicon Valley. . I was given a paper map by a nice rental car lady who said her computer was so slow, and remarked - is that not funny - for being in the high tech capital of the world:) The ATT data service was so overloaded and I had to pull 3 miles away from airport to get a signal for my GPS app. The people at the Airport were very friendly, and I sure was glad to have the paper map as backup if needed :) Also I wanted to buy a kneck pillow for my return flight, but the cheapest one at every single store was 40 Bucks! I expected them to be higher, but that tops anything I have ever seen! They have desk in the gate area, with outlets which is nice. Also there are outlets in a few chairs, which is also helpful. Signage is excellent, which makes it easy to find where to go.<//Text>

<review>This recently renovated airport is convenient for Bay Area travellers,  especially those who live in the South Bay. It is easy to get in and out of the airport with security lines that often move rather quickly. The staff is friendly most of the time. Unlike most airports (both domestic and international) I've been to, the restroom stalls for women are quite spacious with several hooks and shelves to place belongings; they are also very clean.

The restaurant choices are quite good for an airport of this size, with an emphasis on local eateries and shops. CJ Olson Cherries is a good place to stop by for gifts and snacks while Joe's offers good pizzas.

There's also a free shuttle (Bus 10) that takes passengers to and from SJC, Santa Clara Caltrain and Metro Light Rail Station every 15-30 minutes from 5 am to 11:30pm, daily.</review><response>None</response>< time>

< text>
If you want to have lunch or a cocktail with your friends or family before your flight then choose another airport. The terminals are designed to accommodate passengers only. No restaurants, no lounge, few seats and no outlets in sight. Only a small, dark enclosed area for seeing people off, and a newsstand selling soda and mixed nuts. On the plus side, its easy to get to from Amtrak, which earned them a second star.<//text>

< Text>
TSA needs to re-evaluate the security here. They are slow, act like they want to be anywhere else but there, and have no sense of urgency.

I traveled through SJC yesterday and had two small snow globes with me - both fit in a 1 qt bag and under the 3.4oz requirement. They flagged the checkpoint, the agent at x-ray called for a bag check 3 times. it took a few minutes for someone to look up from twiddling their thumbs to come over and check my bag.

While I understand it's up the the agent to let snow globes through, the one I had was a complete jerk about it. He was slow at coming over, rolled his eyes and never made eye contact, and blankly told me I couldn't take them. I asked if I could empty them, he said I would have to go through security again to do it, all the while seeming to not care about anything but getting off work. THEN. I said "I am not going through that line again" - it was SO slow, not enough agents and the ones that were there moved like snails. And he said "fine" and took the globes and put them in a box under the x-ray system. Aren't they supposed to throw them away? Well he didn't and I am sure he has a lovely collection of other people's stuff.

While I can handle not getting the souvenirs for my children, I can't understand the sheer attitude of every TSA agent I encountered there. I fly a lot and have never had a worse experience than I did at San Jose International Airport.</Text>

This airport was great until I had to leave the parking lot. Apparently you need a debit/credit card to leave the parking lot!!! It is suppose to be convenient for patrons not just patrons with plastic!!!!  Anyway I had to back up out of the stall, pull to the side and emergency park. Jump out, find a door into airport then look for a kiosk machine (they take cash, wth?) get my ticket, run back to my car before someone hit it, pay and get out of there. Sheesh that took about 25 minutes. Besides that it was all good. Also there are no humans in the booth upon leaving so it gets confusing as what to do. There should be a HUGE sign before you get the ticket to park, it should state that people with cash have to go to the kiosk machine and get ticket before leaving. <Date>1469029592602< /Date>< rate>
3< /rate>
< review>
Accessing the rental-car parking garage can be a challenge depending on which direction you approach the airport.  Be prepared to drive around the entire airport to make the poorly marked 'rental cars' drop-off lane.

Additionally, instead of having one giant bank of 8 or 10 elevators in the rental car parking garage, they really need to be broken up into two banks of 4 or 5.  Not very well done.

The HVAC needs some work on the gates between the terminals (15 and 16) - the perfume smell wafting down from the duty free store made me nauseous during my wait at the gate.

I do like the abundance of power / USB outlets around the airport - this is the best thing about SJC<//review>

1387587596122< /Time>
<Pics>None</Pics>< review>
It's been a long long long time since I've used SJC and I forgot just how much I like it. For an international airport it is pretty small which means it can be overcrowded but even after all of these years (20-ish) it still wasn't, bot when I arrived and when I departed. Some changes have occurred naturally but all in all it was still as I remember mostly. MUCH better than any other (and I've use MANY) other international airport in the world as far as I'm concerned. Easy to get into and out of, no long wait for baggage, security goes pretty fast and even TSA was respectful and courteous.<//review>

113987573303141584827<//user_id>
< name>
Riad KACED<//name>
<time>1428715270422</time>< Rating>
5< /Rating>
< review>
This is the perfect Airport to fly in/out Silicon Valley. It's a human sized airport with very nice staff. Very well serviced by public transportation. The lines are reasonably short, you got Free Wifi (Welcome to Silicon Valley). There are pretty descent places to eat and drink. Aircrafts takeoff right after leaving the gate, without taxiing forever, same for landing. Baggage comes very quickly as well ! Most importantly, their Airport is kept clean and bathrooms are always clean too. Having moved to the US in the past years where I was disappointed with poor, dirty, unfriendly airport, SJC just stands out and is definitely to the highest standards I used to in Europe and Asia. Keep on the good work !</review>

<rate>5<//rate><Pics>None< /Pics><GmapID>0x808fcbc3fab3c59b:0xbcfa443f6df67e3e<//GmapID><Name>Conrad Paz<//Name><response>None< /response><time>1451677150267</time>< review>
I travel a few times a year from SJC and it is easily accessible by public transit:  light rail and then shuttle.  Driving in is also a breeze.

Plenty of check-in kiosks and security, though the line can be quite long in the mornings, moves briskly. TSA is TSA, so don't expect smiles or pleasant conversations, just straight business.

Enough shops to browse and eateries to grab a bite.  Free WiFi works great and charging chairs throughout the place.

Nice place.<//review>

<review>This is my preferred airport, and is much more accessible for South Bay'ers than either SFO or OAK.  I fly here several times per year.  The terminals are accessible, and I don't usually have to wait long for pickup or dropoff.  I have seen security harass Uber drivers, so be discreet when getting a ride.

The security line isn't too long (generally), but plan at least 20 minutes in line just in case.  The long corridor would really benefit from some moving walkways.  But in all, pretty serviceable.< /review><user_name>Keith Achorn<//user_name>< Time>

<Rating>4</Rating><Review>This is a medium sized airport that's, overall, a lot more pleasant and efficient than SFO.

- A moderate number of food choices.
- The "Lounge at SJC" is pretty nice; not very crowded, and featuring some tasty light bites for lunch and complimentary drinks at the bar.
- Since the airport isn't too huge, you can typically get to your gate in 10 minutes or less from anywhere in your terminal.
- And since fog is rare here in SJ, your plane is much less likely to be delayed due to weather (coming or going) with SJC vs. SFO.<//Review><pics>None< /pics>< Response>

<user>101038348071769313416< /user><text>A real 21st Century airport! I travel all over the world and this just might be my favorite of all. Why? Let me list the reasons:
1. Security took just 5 minutes. I even used passbook on my iPhone with no problem.
2. Free high speed WiFi - I actually watched a couple of You Tube videos and FaceTimed my wife with no lag.
3. Power outlets at EVERY seat! I've been to many other airports where business folks are clustered around the few power outlets hoping to charge up their phones. No problems at SJC!
4. A decent coffee shop (Peets) that isn't Starbucks. Don't get me wrong, they have Starbucks too and it's fine, but I prefer other coffee shops.
5. Car rental across the street. With a passion, I hate arriving at an airport (usually late) and then having to go on a 20 minute bus ride to the rental car center. On the return trip it makes it even worse if you're running late. Why do airports do that? BWI and Denver have ridiculous long bus rides to/from the rental car center. Stupid and inconvenient. SJC, no problem to walk across the street!

All round, a great picture of what a modern airport should be.<//text>< Time>

<name>Thomas Devaux<//name><gmapID>0x808fcbc3fab3c59b:0xbcfa443f6df67e3e</gmapID><text>This is what an airport should be.

I've travelled a lot and I have to say it's one of my favorites.
It's a bit weird to review an airport since it's rarely a place you deliberately chose. But with the proximity of SFO, it can actually be the case.

First of all, it's brand new. From Parking lot to Gates and Rental Car offices, it feels like it was opened yesterday. It also means it's modern in the way it was conceived.

It's quite small. Compared to SFO, you can walk from A to B without having to rush. You can park for 1h right next to the Arrivals if you have to pick someone, it will just cost you $2 or $4.

It's Silicon Valley! They offer free WiFi. All seats in the waiting area have power and USB plugs. Very appreciable. Parkings has NFC payment (great to show off Google Wallet to visiting family!).

These are all good reasons, but the best is it's never crowded. It's much smaller than SFO, so usually it's easy to park and walk. If you're coming to the Bay Area, and not San Francisco itself, you'll find it more convenient.<//text><Rate>5<//Rate>< UserId.>
113348736951055038973</UserId.>
< Pictures>
None<//Pictures>
</record></dataset><record>
< Date>
1395992068505<//Date>
< pictures>
None</pictures>
<Resp>None</Resp><user>103286608250694013489</user>< Review>
Flying in and out of SJC is less of a hassle compared to larger airports such as LAX, SFO, LAS, etc. In a nutshell, this airport needed a major uplift. Thanks to SJ for investing plenty of renovations, it looks absolutely nicer! I LOVE the new Terminal B!! Parking garage is larger, more vroom, vroom, vroom for cars to drive, pick up and drop off passengers for/from flights!!

TSA exceeded my expectations! If you do an early bird check in aka Southwest, AA, etc. You can just drop your luggage off quickly with the attendants and easily go through security lines that don't snake throughout the terminal area. You have enough time to enjoy hanging out at the airport's restaurants, mini bars, and shops.

Although, not much shopping here unless you consider stopping at The Hudson for a small read of their magazines. However, Peet's would be a good choice if you're still groggy for a morning flight. Grab a nice cup of coffee or tea! Unless you're off to Vegas or Miami, maybe a cocktail or beer at The Brit, while watching the news or sports while waiting for your flight, can make the time go by a lot quicker before partying it up in style!

Did I mention, they offer FREE WiFi? Yes! Of course, we're in the heart of Silicon Valley. Many tech companies in the Bay Area. For those who are always busy with work and on the go, don't fret my friends. While waiting for your flight, you can sit down with your laptop and plug it into a power outlet on the side of your seat!! How cool is that?!

Downside to SJC...ticket prices to fly in/out from here is a little bit steep as opposed to SFO or OAK but the extra dollars is worth the trip! Happy travels!</Review>

<UserId.>115664360909293582339</UserId.><username>Andy Aude</username><date>1392683789718<//date>< Rating>
5</Rating>
< Text>
This is a model of a "perfect" airport.

Operational reasons:
Best on-time performance ranking in California.
Weather-delays are exceedingly rare - only 5 days per year.
Not overwhelmingly-busy like SFO.
Good highway/road traffic management.
Somewhat fast TSA lines.

--Amenities--:
Free & Fast WiFi.
Free ground transportation to VTA/Caltrain.
Power outlets in gate areas.
Clean and modern seating areas and bathrooms.

The best domestic carriers:
Virgin, Southwest, Jet Blue. Yay.

Negatives:
All parking (even the "economy lot") can be expensive. $20/day minimum.
Terminal B is nearly a half-mile long (!). That's about a 10 minute walk from end-to-end.<//Text>

(Translated by Google) Since it is not a large airport, the waiting time for each work is relatively short and it goes smoothly overall. There is also a little shopping space at the airport.
International flights are basically Terminal A and domestic flights are Terminal B, but in some cases domestic flights may leave from Terminal A, so it is recommended to check in advance. That was the case before when I went to New York on United Air.
When my parents came to California, I took a direct flight from this airport to Japan. Actually, flights from Japan to San Francisco are cheaper at tens of thousands of yen, but my parents do not have much experience traveling abroad, so I dared to choose a direct flight to this airport so as not to get lost in the airport. My parents also said it wasn't difficult to arrive.
You can rest assured that someone will manage the belt lane when your luggage arrives. The lanes at this airport are short and can quickly fill up with luggage. I was worried that the bag wouldn't break.

(Translated by Google) ANA's check-in counter opens 3 hours before departure. The same applies to the luggage deposit counter. If you want to get in the airport earlier than this, you can do "online check-in" with "only carry-on luggage". You can use "The Club at SJC" with Priority Pass (as of May 2018). In front of Gate 15, often very close to the departure gate for ANA flights. It is about 15 minutes by car from San Jose city, so it is quite close. Baggage inspection takes a considerable amount of time. When crowded, it's better to wait for an hour just in case.
